<TITLE> Barroso: Polish concerns should not stop EU treaty </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, Sept 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - It should be possible to address Polish concerns over a new EU treaty and ensure it can be completed at an upcoming summit, European Commission President Jose Manuel Barroso said in Warsaw on Thursday. Poland's eurosceptic ruling Kaczynski twins want a mechanism to delay EU decisions in the treaty and could still be a possible obstacle to completing the charter designed to reform EU institutions. Barroso discussed the treaty with Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski and was later to meet twin brother Lech, the president. "Prime Minister Kaczynski explained to me some of the specific concerns of Poland in this matter," Barroso said. "I really believe...there should be no political, possible problem there. I think it is possible to find technical solutions that will respond to the concerns of all the member states." The Kaczynskis fought with EU partners ahead of a summit on the new treaty in June and won a delay in implementation of a new voting system they fear will give too much power to bigger states. Later, they demanded that the treaty include a clear mechanism allowing countries to be able to put off EU decisions if they were just short of enough votes to block them. The timing of next month's summit, where EU presidency holder Portugal hopes to complete the treaty, is particularly sensitive for Poland because it is days ahead of an early parliamentary election on Oct. 21. The Kaczynskis' conservative Law and Justice party faces a tough challenge from the centre-right Civic Platform, which is much more pro-EU and is favoured by markets for its pro-business agen
